        "title": "Top 10 records of 2012",
        "body": "<p>2012, like any year, didn&rsquo;t disappoint in the music department. I was contemplating making one of these lists this year. I guess the main reason I am doing it is more a to create a list of what I listened to this year and suggest you check them out if you haven&rsquo;t already. I did listened to more music than this over the course of the year, but these ones stood out. So without further ado, here are my favorite records of 2012.</p>\n\n<p><b>The Snips: <i>Highs of Low</i></b> - I&rsquo;d only heard of The Snips prior to listening to this record. I heard a song on a podcast in the spring and went to check it out. Turns out the record is <a href=\"http://thesnips.com/\">free to download off their website</a> so began listening right away. I instantly became a fan. The sounds are very melodic and I love the singers voice. I ended up revisiting it many times throughout the year.</p>\n\n<p><b>The Holy Mess: <i>Cande Ru Las Degas</i></b> - I knew these guys were recording at some point and was anticipating this release. It didn&rsquo;t disappoint at all and is probably my favorite form the list. Good old gruff punk from Philadelphia.</p>\n\n<p><b>Propagandhi: <i>Failed States</i></b> - These guys keep taking each record to the next level. I know I am probably in the minority but I liked their last record (<i>Supporting Caste</i>) better. Some of the song&rsquo;s lyrics are somewhere I can&rsquo;t get to and don&rsquo;t really want to. With that being said I think musically they hit it out of the park with this one.</p>\n\n<p><b>Menzingers: <i>On the Impossible Past</i></b> - I loved their last record and this one was a bit more polished. The songs were a little slower and it took me a bunch of spins for it to click but it finally did. The final product is, to me, timeless.</p>\n\n<p><b>No trigger: <i>Tycoon</i></b> - If you read my blog you know I&rsquo;ve not only been anticipating this record but hyping it as well. Even though they haven&rsquo;t put out a record in like 7 years it&rsquo;s as if they never missed a beat. Which make me think how ahead of it&rsquo;s time Canyoneer was. Every song on this record is great. </p>\n\n<p><b>Bruce Springsteen: <i>Wrecking Ball</i></b> - What can I say? I&rsquo;m a big fan of The Boss but haven&rsquo;t been blown away by anything he&rsquo;s put out in the last 10 years. This record was an exception. The song Wrecking Ball is one of those that I think could live on forever.</p>\n\n<p><b>Teeange Bottlerocket: Freak Out!</b> - I don&rsquo;t know why it took me so long to get into this band. Granted the super poppy punk has been done a million times but these guys nail it. Even the jokier songs are good. If there is one band I want to see live in 2013 it&rsquo;s these guys.</p>\n\n<p><b>Daytrader: <i>12 Years</i></b> - This was kind of a guilty pleasure. Even though I kind of dug the E.P. they put out last year I saw them play a show and was unimpressed . This full length was a great next step for the band. It has some super catchy songs on it. It&rsquo;s too bad they broke up before the year was over.</p>\n\n<p><b>Anchors: <i>Lost at the Bottom of the World</i></b> - Another solid release from a band that I don&rsquo;t think gets much love from the media. I had no idea this record was out until near the end of the year. Every song is solid. It&rsquo;s just good, catchy, fast punk that seems to be missing these days.</p>\n\n<p><b>NOFX: <i>Self-Entitled</i></b> - To me, NOFX hasn&rsquo;t released anything groundbreaking in the last 15 years but I do own and really like everything they&rsquo;ve done. This record was great. It was was simple with no joke songs. You can hear many Bad Religion influences throughout it. It had a rawness to it as well that created a refreshing, back-to-basics sound.</p>",
