        "description": "<p>No one has ever asked me &ldquo;How should I go about learning linux?&rdquo;. Fortunately, these days, linux has come a long way since I started using it back in 2002. I graduated college a few years later and at the time the computer science and/or engineering lab at WMU were switching over all the computers they had from Red Hat to <a href=\"http://www.gentoo.org/\">Gentoo</a>. I wasn&rsquo;t sure the reason or why they didn&rsquo;t go with fedora but I think it had something to do with the flexibility of Gentoo. I was listening to <a href=\"http://twit.tv/show/floss-weekly/212\">FLOSS Weekly</a> the other day and it inspired me to say something. </p>\n\n<p>I <a href=\"http://blog.joefearnley.com/post/1039732576/gentau\">ran gentoo</a> up until a couple of years ago and eventually gave up. I only have so much time in my life for <a href=\"http://sethgodin.typepad.com/seths_blog/2005/03/dont_shave_that.html\">yak shaving</a> and this is pretty much the worst as far as I&rsquo;ve encountered. But once you get things figured out it all kind of starts to make sense and the power of such a distribution comes clear. Eventually you can graduate to using <a href=\"http://www.gentoo.org/doc/en/genkernel.xml\">Genkernel</a>. </p> \n\n<p>The bottom line is if you really want to learn how linux works, bring yourself up to speed with the command line enough to handle <a href=\"http://www.gentoo.org/doc/en/handbook/\">the handbook</a>, <a href=\"http://www.gentoo.org/main/en/mirrors2.xml\">download a stage 3 tarball</a> and get your install on. It will be challenging and you will encounter many radblocks along the way but I guarantee you will learn plenty. </p>",
