                "content_raw": "<p>I recently starting building <a href=\"https://github.com/joefearnley/highfashion\">a small application</a> in python. The is simple, it just does basic server-side logging. Shortly into the development of it I realized I wanted to include some options for how the application works. The main delema that came up was where to actually log the data to. A database? The filesystem? An external service? Then how about a debug flag for development? </p>\n\n<p>I soon realized I needed some way to do configuration. In the past when developing with Python this has been done by using whatever the framework does in <a href=\"https://www.djangoproject.com/\">Django</a> or <a href=\"http://bottlepy.org/\">Bottle</a>. I initially created this application for a basic need and because I wanted to try out <a href=\"http://flask.pocoo.org/\">Flask</a>, which in part of it’s beauty, leaves this up to you. I looked into what the <a href=\"http://flask.pocoo.org/docs/config/\">Flask documentation suggested </a>and it was pretty straight forward. The Flask object actually has a config subclass (config) that you can get/set values to. The part in question was getting the initial configuration into that subclass. This is where I began to struggle.</p>\n\n<p>I wanted to figure out what the best way to do this in Python. Or the “Pythonic” way. Coming from a Java background, this sort of thing is done in an xml or .properties file. In PHP it’s suggested to to use a class or a basic config.php file with a array of constants. After a bit of searching, I couldn’t really find a “Pythonic” way to do this. Sure I could always use an xml, or better yet, json file. I could use a config.py file, environment variables, a .ini file…the options are endless.</p>\n\n<p>After revisiting the Flask documentation, I decided on a suggested pattern described there. Using inheritance, create a base class named Config. Then extend that class with a class that correlates to your current environment (prod, dev, test…) then pull the one you want into your main Flask object. This seemed simple enough but I still don’t know if this is the best way to do and honestly, don’t know if I ever will.</p>\n\n<p>Maybe I am looking to far into this but when learning something I want to start out the “right” way to prevent developing bad habits. But sometimes, I get too wrapped up in what is the “right” way and before I know it I am several hours into something and have nothing to show for it.</p> \n\n<p>There is definitely a couple lessons to be learned here. Sometimes I just gotta say screw it, start building something and worry about the details later. Unfortunately in software development this can cause major headaches down the road. The main thing I want to take away from situations like this is what I’ve learned.</p>",
