        "title": "Using Github to host static websites",
        "body": "<p>On my continued quest to move away from paid hosting for the websites I maintain, I started to explore what options are out there to complete this. Last fall I <a href=\"http://blog.joefearnley.com/post/1253242465/gitin-a-hold-on-things\">moved my blog to tumblr and created a landing page for joefearnley.com at github</a>. The next step was to get a few static html sites moved somewhere, preferably for free. I found <a href=\"http://www.nata2.org/2011/01/26/how-to-use-app-engine-to-host-static-sites-for-free/\">a post on Harper Reed&rsquo;s site</a> explaining how to do this with Google App Engine using <a href=\"http://drydrop.binaryage.com/\">drydrop</a>. This was a fine solution but I soon realized it was possible to do this with with github which seemed a little more appealing to me.</p>\n\n<p>I realized that github users can created what are called <a href=\"http://pages.github.com/\">Project Pages</a> to create websites for each project and point a custom domain name to it like I did with <a href=\"http://joefearnley.com\">joefearnley.com</a>. There you can host HTML/CSS/JavaScript files (or apps along with essentially any other files types) for free. Then if I ever want to makes any changes to these sites I can do so locally, push the changes to github and have the live site updated on the fly. Pretty interesting, huh? Let me explain how I went about doing this.</p>\n\n<p><i><strong>Disclaimer</strong>. This could be violating Github&rsquo;s Terms of Service. I can&rsquo;t tell for sure. All I can say is proceed with caution.</i></p>\n\n<p>First things first, created a new repository for your site and push your files there. If you are new to git and or github they have some <a href=\"http://help.github.com/create-a-repo/\">great documentation</a> how to do this.</p>\n\n<p>Next, create new <a href=\"http://pages.github.com/\">Pages</a> branch in your repo. Make sure you explicityly name it &ldquo;gh-pages&rdquo; (see the <a href=\"https://help.github.com/categories/20/articles\">Pages documentation</a> on the easier ways to do this). Here is how I went about doing this part: </p>\n\n<pre>\nmacbook:tweenis joe$ git checkout gh-pages \nSwitched to branch 'gh-pages'\nmacbook:tweenis joe$ \n</pre>\n\n\n<p></p>\n\n<p></p>\n\n<p>In the case for static sites, I choose the following workflow:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Make changes on the master branch (or a different branch, then merge to master for keeping things a decoupled)\n<pre>\nmacbook:tweenis joe$ git commit -a -m 'Adding from master branch'\n[gh-pages afc3118] adding all files from master branch\n 16 files changed, 661 insertions(+), 77 deletions(-)\n create mode 100644 CNAME\n create mode 100644 README.md\n create mode 100644 about.html\n create mode 100644 images/bg.jpg\n create mode 100644 images/bullet.gif\n create mode 100644 images/clock.gif\n create mode 100644 images/comment.gif\n create mode 100644 images/firefox-gray.jpg\n create mode 100644 images/gradientbg.jpg\n create mode 100644 images/headerphoto.jpg\n create mode 100644 images/page.gif\n create mode 100644 images/tweenis.jpg\n rewrite index.html (98%)\n create mode 100644 js/jquery-1.3.2.min.js\n create mode 100644 js/tweenis.js\n create mode 100644 style/style.css\nmacbook:tweenis joe$\n</pre>\n</li>\n<li>\nMerge &ldquo;production&rdquo; changes to the gh-pages branch\n<pre>\nmacbook:tweenis joe$ git merge gh-pages\nMerge made by recursive.\n index.html |    4 ++--\n 1 files changed, 2 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-)\nmacbook:tweenis joe$ \n</pre>\n</li>\n\n<li>\nPush changes back to Github\n<pre>\nmacbook:tweenis joe$ git push \nTotal 0 (delta 0), reused 0 (delta 0)\nTo git@github.com:joefearnley/tweenis.git\n   df8865f..4b1837e  gh-pages -&gt; gh-pages\nmacbook:tweenis joe$ \n</pre>\n</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>I&rsquo;m a command-line guy and if you are not I would consider using one of the <a href=\"http://mac.github.com/\">github</a> <a href=\"http://windows.github.com/\">clients</a>. I haven&rsquo;t used either of them so I can&rsquo;t attest to whether or not it will make things easier but it is worth a shot.</p>",
