        "title": "Convert string to Packed ASCII byte array",
        "body": "<p>For a project at working on at my day job, I was required to utilize a form of data compression called Packed ASCII. In my case I was writing data as a string to <a href=\"http://www.hartcomm.org/\">HART</a> devices. Here is the formal definition:</p>\n\n<p><i>Packed ASCII is a HART-specific 6-bit character code representing a subset of the ASCII character code set. Produced by compressing four Packed ASCII characters into three 8-bit bytes, Packed ASCII string must be a multiple of 4 characters (3bytes) and must be padded out to the end of the data item with space characters. For example 4 space characters at the end of a string would appear as the 3 bytes: 0x82, 0x80, and 0x20.</i></p>\n\n<p>In order to create a Packed ASCII string, you must remove the most significant bits from each character in the string then combine the results. Basically there are three main steps to create a Packed ASCII string:</p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Truncate bit 6 and 7 of the ASCII character.</li>\n<li>Pack four, 6-bit ASCII characters into three bytes.</li>\n<li>Repeat until the string is fully processed.</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>An example of this would be converting the string “JOEY”. </p>\n\n<pre>\nJ: 01001010\nO: 01001111\nE: 01000101\nY: 01011001\n</pre>\n\n<p>To get just the bottom 6 bits, you need to perform the following bit-wise operation on each byte:</p>\n\n<pre>\nx &amp; 0x3F (00111111)\n</pre>\n\n<p>For the String &ldquo;JOEY&rdquo;, you would do the following:</p>\n\n<pre>\nJ &amp; 0x3F = 01001010 &amp; 00111111 = 00001010\nO &amp; 0x3F = 01001111 &amp; 00111111 = 00001111\nE &amp; 0x3F = 01000101 &amp; 00111111 = 00000101\nY &amp; 0x3F = 01011001 &amp; 00111111 = 00011001\n</pre>\n\n<p>Then combine the groups of four truncated bytes into three full bytes:</p>\n\n<pre>\n001010 001111 000101 011001 = 00101000 11110001 01011001 = 0x28 0xF1 0x59\n</pre>\n\n<p>So basically we convert the given string into a byte array, iterate over it packing groups of four bytes into three and adding these to a list. The method in C# ends up looking something like this:</p>\n\n<p class=\"embed_gist\"><a href=\"http://gist.github.com/1097708\">http://gist.github.com/1097708</a></p> \n\n<p>One thing to note is the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Endian\">endianness</a> of the architecture of the machine the code is being run on. In certain cases the results of the bit manipulations may need to be reversed.</p>\n\n<p>So now you have a method to create a packed-ASCII byte array, what do you do with it? In my case I had to send data in a string of hexadecimal values separated by a space. I also had to make sure the hexadecimal pairs were complete. For instance &ldquo;A&rdquo; is not equal to &ldquo;0A&rdquo; so I had to add the preceding &ldquo;0&rdquo; value to each one. The result looked something like this: </p>\n\n<p class=\"embed_gist\"><a href=\"http://gist.github.com/1097750\">http://gist.github.com/1097750</a></p> \n\n<p>I could not have done this with out the help of Andy W. Thanks, Andy, I learned a lot.</p>",
