                "content": "<p><p>I came across <a href=\"http://www.pcworld.com/article/190205/are_hollywood_hackers_bogus_or_bright.html?tk=rss_news\">this article</a> on <a href=\"http://digg.com/\">digg</a> the other day and it me got thinking about all of the movies and television shows I&rsquo;ve seen in the last twenty years that included that scene where they are reviewing some sort of security tape. It usually has the investigator, partner and techie guy that can &ldquo;enhance&rdquo; the video or image to the investigator&rsquo;s request. The funny part about it is that it&rsquo;s pretty much the same scene except the newer ones might contain a touch screen. I don&rsquo;t much about forensic technology today, but I think it&rsquo;s safe to say that once something is pixelated, the closer you get, the worse it gets. If it does get better, your software&rsquo;s probably just guessing. Regardless, <a href=\"http://digg.com/users/CapeKid\">capekid </a>on digg post this video in the comments and it totally hit home with me.\n\n</p>\n<p><a href=\"#\"><img src=\"https://assets.tumblr.com/images/inline_placeholder.png\" width=\"18\" height=\"14\"/></a></p>\n</p>",
