        "title": "sunday social #35 - aggregation",
        "body": "<p>I had to explain to my brother what <a title=\"twitter\" href=\"http://twitter.com\">twitter</a> was today. This wasn&rsquo;t the first time I had to do this and if anyone out there has had to do this, you know the world I entered this afternoon was a very confusing one. If you have had to do this, and never stopped and had the thought that twitter was a wick ridiculous, there might be something way too web 2.0 in you. Whats a wick? Well that&rsquo;s a different story all together.</p>\n\n<p>Thinking back, roughly a year and a half ago, I decided to sign up for <a title=\"http://twitter.com/joefearnley\" href=\"http://twitter.com/joefearnley\">this service</a>. I just looked back at some of my tweets and got a good laugh. Do people really care about what I have to say or am doing? I don&rsquo;t know. Rachel, Dawn, and even sometimes Lexy used to give me shit about using it. They&rsquo;d ask me to actually say I was composing a &ldquo;tweet&rdquo;, then get a laugh. A little gaslight anthem if you will. Who am I though.</p>\n\n<p>In a quick response and total ripoff of <a title=\"http://cursebird.com/\" href=\"http://cursebird.com/\">curse bird</a>, I decided to whip up <a title=\"tweenis\" href=\"http://tweenis.net\">tweenis</a> yesterday. Oh yeah, and its real time&hellip;as much as that can be. A lot of talk about watch men.</p>\n\n<p>Still, years and years after its use, demise, then rebirth, so many people cannot distinguish the difference between between <a title=\"java\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Java_(programming_language)\">java</a> and <a title=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/JavaScript\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/JavaScript\">javascript</a>. Not passing judgment. That probably should have been a tweet.</p>\n\n<p>After getting knee deep in the twitter API and seven budwiesers later, I hit up papa petes for the <a title=\"http://www.mustardplug.com/\" href=\"http://www.mustardplug.com/\">mustard plug</a> show. Shit hasn&rsquo;t changed since I saw them in the mid-nineties at the Kalamazoo state theater. And I am so glad it hasn&rsquo;t. The beer song has never sounded so good. But this time, while drinking a beer.</p>\n\n<p>As for me, I&rsquo;m getting ready for the working week. See you in wednesday.</p>",
