        "title": "I know exactly who think I am",
        "body": "<p>So I created <a title=\"who do I think I am\" href=\"http://joef.org/2008/11/06/who-do-think-i-am/\">a post</a> last week and had some time to think about it over the weekend. I came to the conclusion that it really doesn&rsquo;t matter how bad my grammar is or that I can&rsquo;t correctly form sentences. Its all about the content. The more the better. That right. As long as I keep cranking out this blog posts, something&rsquo;s got to give. Even if I have no idea what that something is.</p>\n\n<p>Now to the real reason I created this post. I read <a title=\"http://www.punknews.org/article/31204\" href=\"http://www.punknews.org/article/31204\">this article</a> tonight and it got me thinking again. I realized (again, thinking) that I was actually thinking while away from work, so I thought the world should know. This is the beginning of the end people. These labels are dropping like flies trying to re-invent themselves.</p>\n\n<p>The even weirder part was shortly after reading this article, I saw <a title=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aly_&amp;_AJ\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aly_&amp;_AJ\">these two chicks</a> on mtv cribs. I don&rsquo;t know how old this episode is, but how have I not heard of these two? With all of these labels falling by the wayside and a plethora of good music out there today, its hard to understand how these girls are on mtv and that they are obviously making money.</p>\n\n<p>Its OK though, I&rsquo;m not bitter. Their sixteen and have brand new benz. I am twenty-six and have a scion. At least I know how to operate mine. And mudvayne has gone easy listening. Maybe its more marketable to the mtv generation?</p>",
