        "note_count": 0,
        "title": "blah blah blah, problem self imposed",
        "body": "<p><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/joefearnley/1155245080/\" title=\"IMAGE_076 by joefearnley, on Flickr\"><img src=\"http://farm2.static.flickr.com/1336/1155245080_cf45172410_t.jpg\" alt=\"IMAGE_076\" style=\"margin: 5px; float: right\" height=\"80\" width=\"100\"/></a></p>\n\n<p>Lets take a moment to talk about the current state of the music industry. I am really fascinated by all the predictions being made by those currently in the industry and those who aren&rsquo;t. Obviously you got those executives and many others alike who are holding to this dieing model of how things should be handled. It seems these are the ones with a whole shitload to lose. Yet currently still have all of the power. Now <a href=\"http://www.punknews.org\" title=\"punk news\">I read the articles</a> and <a href=\"http://www.issueoriented.com/\" title=\"issue oriented\">listen to the podcasts</a> and everyone has got the ideas but it seems like none of them will ever work.</p>\n\n<p>There are some who may have found a way out (or in?). Take the guy jeff from <a href=\"http://www.bombthemusicindustry.com/\" title=\"bomb the music industry\">bomb the music industry</a>. Since day one he has a pretty clear vision and stuck to that vision very well. It says it right there in the name of his band. Create the music, give it away for free, and get out there and entertain. And he takes it one step further but not selling t-shirts, just spraying a fan&rsquo;s shirt with paint and a stencil. Now this ladies and gents is what music is all about. Does he make a living from making music? I highly doubt it. But he is building a solid fanbase and being the on the other side of the spectrum that doesn&rsquo;t really have much to lose.</p>\n\n<p>Really, you dont even have to get out there and entertain if you don&rsquo;t want to, but most feel they owe it to their fans. I know many who could care less about going and seeing their favorite musical act perform. This must be a wonderful time for them. But me, I live for that part of an artist. This also makes me think about the notion of all of these bands currently on tour. Many say its because bands can&rsquo;t make money selling records. I suppose music has become  so damn disposable that the only thing left is the live show.  For myself, I am becoming less and less concerned on whether or not I own the cd, but rather that the band is coming to michigan.</p>\n\n<p>I&rsquo;m not saying this is the first time these things have been said. I just want to say that I am really excited to see where the future of all this takes us and hope it doesn&rsquo;t suck. Just saying.</p>\n\n<p>Joe</p>",
