        "title": "deck the halls",
        "body": "<p>First things first - update on the site. Because of my half-ass, amateur database design, it will be a huge pain to put pagination in this site. The only place it would pertain to is the archive pages, so really its no big deal. I mean, I only post something about every two months, so the length of the archive page wont get that big before I begin development on joef.org 2.0. Which, once <a href=\"http://labs.joef.org/\">the lab&rsquo;s site</a> comes full circle, and I get bored enough, it should begin. I got some ideas in lingering and an object-oriented approach to boot.</p>\n\n<p>Which leads me to the another thing I want to talk about. Thanks to <a href=\"http://www.myspace.com/rydaly\">Ryan Daly</a> hanging out at my house last weekend, I have discovered a new love for <a href=\"http://www.google.com\">google</a>. I never took the plunged into <a href=\"http://www.google.com/ig?hl=en\">the personalized version</a>, but since last weekend, my web surfing experience has taken a complete turn. These dudes are leading the way with this web 2.0 phenom, and as much as I want to shy away, I just cant.</p><p>On to the <a href=\"http://www.google.com/ig?hl=en\">personlized google page</a>, I log into google one time (as long as you keep your cookies in tact) and every time I type visit the site, I feel like I have the web at my finger tips. Not only do I have my gmail feed, google calender, and weather right there, I can add virtually any other feeds I want. I got the latest headlines from <a href=\"http://www.digg.com/\">digg</a>, <a href=\"http://www.punknews.org\">punknews.org</a>, and yes, that&rsquo;s right, the <a href=\"http://joef.org/rss\">joef.org</a> as well. Its true, my custom <a href=\"http://joef.org/rss\">rss feed</a> really does work (at least on google)! Also, on another, the latest version of firefox has this spell checker built in and it does wonders for my illiterate ass.</p>\n\n<p>In other news, we got to test out the deck this past weekend. It was a wonderful experience. Hamburgers, beers, drumsets and good weather. Nothing like hearing beats played at 7 a.m. with the sound reverberating off the state theater wall. You really cant be that for a saturday. </p>\n\n<p>Again, <a href=\"http://labs.joef.org/\">the lab</a> is coming along to. I have recordings in the works. I will have a separate section of the lab&rsquo;s site dedicated to this. Its gonna be great! I also have my latest linux box (none more laptop) running full swing. So, unfortunately, I no more excuses&hellip;.</p>\n\n<p>joe</p>",
