        "title": "on the move",
        "body": "<p>So my current residnece is begin sold and ray and I are on our way out. Looking for a new place, I am thinking how I am going to reinvent <a href=\"http://labs.joef.org\">the lab</a>. If <a href=\"http://www.peregrinetowers.com/res_122_lovell.htm\">the place we want to live</a> becomes the new home, the thoughts are endless. </p>\n\n<p>In other news, I am continuing to record music in <a href=\"http://labs.joef.org\">the lab</a> and have a couple songs wrttien. No words yet, just music. And honestly, they are fairly poor. But you have any start some where. </p>\n\n<p>This leads my to bring up my sound delema. I am looking for a good distortion pedal to create the great sound I am looking for until I can afford a new amplifier. I am looking at either <a href=\"http://www.procosound.com/ratindex.htm#rat2\">the rat</a>, <a href=\"http://www.procosound.com/ratindex.htm#turbo\">the turbo rat</a>, or the <a href=\"http://www.bbesound.com/products/stomp_boxes/Crusher/index.asp\">the bbe crusher</a>. Unfortunately none of the music shops in town carry them so I cannot personally test them out. I am looking for a good, thick crunchy distortoin (marshall like) for under $100. I am open to anyone with suggestions.</p>\n\n<p>I know a new pedal wont get me that far, but somewhere closer that I currently am. If my new residence allows me to play loud music, I may just forgo the pedal and use the money toward a new amplifier. I realize what I have right now just isnt going to cut it if I ever want to play in a band or perform music live. </p>\n\n<p>joe</p>",
