        "note_count": 0,
        "title": "molson for everyone",
        "body": "<p>So, I have made some modifications to my site recently. Nothing big, just added a section for current readings and those neat little rss <a href=\"http://feedicons.com\">feed icons</a>. Still got the <a href=\"http://www.danbrown.com/novels/davinci_code/reviews.html\">davinci code</a> on the reading list, but will soon be off. I cant seem to get into this one like I did <a href=\"http://www.danbrown.com/novels/angels_demons/reviews.html\">angels and demons</a>. Who knows.</p>\n\n<p>In other news, I got the latest version of <a href=\"http://www.ubuntu.com/\">ubuntu</a> installed on the <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/joefearnley/91270515/\">mac mini</a>. Seeing as I was having a hard time with the OSX interface, and as how I seem to take a liking to the <a href=\"http://gnome.org\">gnome</a> one, I thought it would be perfect to try it out and see what happens. After first trying a <a href=\"http://gentoo.org\">gentoo</a> install and a kernel compilation error, <a href=\"http://www.ubuntu.com/\">ubuntu</a> was a no brainer. The installation was like butter, up and running in no time. The only problem I encountered was the wireless networking (apparently the cards info was not released to the open source community so some dude had to reverse engineer it). So if anyone has questions about getting the airport extreme card woking with <a href=\"http://www.ubuntu.com/\">ubuntu</a>, let me know. I now have my sites set on the <a href=\"http://www.griffintechnology.com/products/imic/\">iMic</a>. </p>\n\n<p>For the future of this site, I am seeing a *beer of the month* section.  Yes, thats right, beer of the month. But this wont be anything that will make me look sophisticated, it will be more like the never-ending variaties of malt liquor. All in all, this enhancement will bring the version of my site out of beta. Sweet.</p>\n\n<p>joe</p>",
